It depends on the setting, theme, and the male character's background. In general I don't tend to describe viewpoint characters too much, because I often find it rather jarring. Everyone hates the whole "and then the character looked in the mirror and gave a detailed description of themselves". So it tends to come up naturally, or so I hope.

Say it just takes place in the modern world, then the character is very likely to be an everyman. But say I decide to make the story about a /fit/ anthro with abs you can bounce quarters off then the character might be /fit/ himself, or on the other hand a guy who's trying to get into shape. If I'm writing military science fiction type stuff chances are very good he's going to be a beefcake, because you can't be a space marine without being a beefcake.

It relies on the female anthro in so far as it's fun to play off, if I'm even doing that. And I usually don't, especially if the anthro's physical description is already out of the ordinary. If she's unusually big or small, she'll still be that way even if the male character is unusually big or small for a human. In fact, the two of them being relatively close together in terms of size sets you up for a story where the male character is drawn out of his habit of seeing himself as the largest/smallest person in the room.

>When it comes to "Anon" How do you build them up?
Since I don't exclude any POV, it's unfair to single the second person ones out.
I wrote a rather long piece where the first draft was in second person, with the caveats that I never called him Anon (obviously the other characters knew his name) and that he never used first person pronouns. No I, no we.
When I went for a second draft, I'd learned who he was at the story's end. The character became clear, and small details I'd had for the observant reader became important. While I wanted a specific build from the start, the character told me the rest.
Everything else I've written has a similar result. The characters tell me. Whether or not I state it plainly, I had something in mind. I'd rather not waste several hundred words on an infodumped biography.

>They're normally always taller, stronger...than the protagonist (Anon)
There's nothing wrong with this if needed. It can lead to poor plotting, and tends to ignore basic physics and biomechanics. Not everything needs to be hard scifi justified.

>making him, (you) the full on opposite?
Same as above. Give the damned character a good motivation and setting, develop a reason for the setting/size/anthros.

>these anthro bitches are in full on heat and rape mode
As cringey as it could end up, this comes back to a point I struggled with in one of my pieces. Every sentient species is on a different reproductive cycle. Sentience means you aren't reduced to feral & animalistic behavior. So my humans have the best endurance (slower, but energizer bunny) & the best throwing skills. Another had the best sense of smell, but about 1/8 of what their non-sentient relatives would. So everything works out to a stalemate, yet what I envisioned as a twist on our world ended up interesting to me and as of yet largely unexplored.
My advice: figure at most four general rules. Three is great, two might be too little unless the species differences suit that, five will get too specific and busy. Build up your world, figure where the conflict is.
To paraphrase something out of Iain M. Banks' Culture books, the average Culture citizen is really fucking boring. The average Special Circumstances operative is the opposite.
You've got a fragment of the conflict needed. Poke at that setting and what you receive back is the story.
